

// forensic-style BitLocker password recovery workflow on Parrot OS using:
	
		John the Ripper
		Hashcat
	
	BUT this should ONLY be done if:
	
		// Blair is authorized to access the data, the drive belongs to the organization, and recovery is legitimate.

// This process does NOT “break” BitLocker directly.
// It attempts to:

		extract a password-verification hash,
		then test possible passwords against it.

// If the original password is: weak, reused, predictable, recovery MAY succeed.

// If the password was strong: recovery may be computationally infeasible.


PHASE 1 — Identify the BitLocker Partition

	Run:

		lsblk -f
		
		
PHASE 2 — Install Required Tools

// Update repositories

		sudo apt update

// Install John + forensic tools

		sudo apt install john hashcat git python3-pip dislocker -y

		
PHASE 3 — Install bitlocker2john

// bitlocker2john is sometimes bundled with John Jumbo.

	# Check first (run):

		which bitlocker2john
		

	# If Found, Good — continue.	
	
			# If NOT Found, Clone John Jumbo (run):

				git clone https://github.com/openwall/john.git		

			# Go into source (run):

				cd john/src		

			# Build it:

				./configure make -sj$(nproc)

			# Then:

				cd ../run

			# Check:

				ls | grep bitlocker

			# You should see:

				bitlocker2john.py
				
	
